context: The earliest known use of the phrase <b4_0><b11_0>Brytish Iles<b11_0/><b4_0/> in the English language is dated <a1_0><b8_0>1577<b8_0/><a1_0/> in <a0_0>a work by <b5_0>John Dee<b5_0/><a0_0/>. Today, this name is seen by some as carrying imperialist overtones although it is still commonly used. Other names used to describe the islands include the <a2_0><b9_0>Anglo-Celtic Isles<a2_0/>, Atlantic archipelago, British-Irish Isles, Britain and Ireland, UK and Ireland, and British Isles and Ireland.<b9_0/> Owing to political and national associations with the word British, the Government of Ireland does not use the term <b6_0><b12_0>British Isles<b12_0/><b6_0/> and in documents drawn up jointly between the <b7_0>British and Irish governments<b7_0/>, the archipelago is referred to simply as <a3_0>"these islands<a3_0/>". Nonetheless, <b10_0>British Isles<b10_0/> is still the most widely accepted term for the archipelago.
